^-|CS|4|CP||at|^C@2^Y@3I|FP||AT|n terms of point ranges, there is not universal agreement. However, many people play what is known as |cp|8|at|"good-bad"|cp||at| Michaels (and the same treatment could be applied to the unusual NT). They play that Michaels either shows a bad hand (|cp|8|at|no more than 9 HCP|cp||at|) or a good hand (|cp|8|at|more than 16 HCP|cp||at|). With an intermediate hand and the appropriate 5/5 shape, the overcaller simply bids his higher ranking suit. The reasoning behind this is that, with the bad hand the Michaels bidder is planning to pass whatever suit partner chooses; with a good hand, the Michaels bidder is planning to jump to game in whatever suit partner chooses.|
PG| ***** 198 ***** |


CS|4|FP|2|AT|^-

{Michaels can also be played over preempts}
^-|FP||CS||AT|

It is particularly useful over minor suit preempts. A cue bid over a minor suit preempt shows at least 5/5 in the majors, and asks partner to bid his best major. Typically, you should have a pretty strong hand (|cp|8|at|at least 14 points in the 2 suits|cp||at|), because, even over a weak 2@D, you are forcing the bidding to the 3 level, and over 3@C/3@D you are forcing the bidding to game. You can also bid Michaels over major suit preempts, but often an overcall of the other major is more useful. You have to use your judgement.|
